    rococo: {
        name: "Rococo",
        key_timespan: "1710 - 1790",
        quick_take: "Ornate, theatrical. Pastel whites, pale yellows, pearl grays, pinks, baby blues, mint greens and gold gilding. Superficial, degenerate, illogical, frivolous, erotic, excessively ornate. Cherubs, seashells, twisting vines, broad leaves, branches, musical instruments, garlands of fruits and flowers. Ornately framed mirrors, multicolored venetian glass chandelers. White stucco material and illusionary wall, ceiling painting.",
        inspired_feelings: "Mildly erotic, amorous, romantic, frivolous. Feel an air of aristocractic sophistication. Be surprised, awed with the amount of stylish ornamentation.",
        why_you_should_you_care: "Seen extensively and across many forms of arts. An extremely popular art style across most of Europe seen often in residential salons, palaces, buildings and aristocratic settings.",
        why_it_evolved: "A reaction against the Style Louis XIV and his reign having featured majesty, formality, geometry, harmony and regularity. Rococo developed by craftspeople and designers rather than architects, so found primarily in furniture, silver and ceramics.",
        why_it_ended: "The style-leading French art establishment preferred a more noble, grande, serious, symmetrical and grounded in antiquity - a neo-classical art direction influenced by the discoveries of Roman antiquities at Herculaneum and Pompeii.",
        uniqueness: "A style without rules. Exuberant decoration, with an abundance of curves, counter-curves, undulations and elements modeled on nature. The exteriors of buildings are often simple, while the interiors are entirely dominated by their ornament. Highly theatrical style. Floor plans of churches were often complex, featuring interlocking ovals; In palaces, grand stairways became centrepieces, and offered different points of view of the decoration. Asymmetrical shells, acanthus and other leaves, birds, bouquets of flowers, fruits, musical instruments, angels and Chinoiserie (pagodas, dragons, monkeys, bizarre flowers and Chinese people). Painted scenes of passion and intimate amorous subjects.",
        relevant_history: "It was a favored style of Madame de Pompadour, the official Chief Mistress of Louis XV. Often used to add eroticism to various collections.",
        opinions_and_commentary: "\"...ridiculous jumble of shells, dragons, reeds, palm-trees and plants\". Sometimes used as a term for out of style and old-fashioned belonging to the style of the 18th century. A fantasy-based \"aristocratic\" art. An insult upon the rights of men. A \"petit\" (small) style, not a grand, noble style.",
        style: "Differs from Baroque with the: partial abandonment of symmetry, everything being composed of graceful lines and curves; the huge quantity of asymmetrical curves and C-shaped volutes; the very wide use of flowers in ornamentation, an example being festoons made of flowers; Chinese and Japanese motifs; warm pastel colours (whitish-yellow, cream-colored, pearl greys, very light blues). Rococo uses: explosions of forms that cascaded down the walls; elaborately ornate framed mirrors and multicolored venetian glass; illusionist ceiling paintings (trompe-l'œil).",
        typical_subjects: "Passionate, mildly erotic and intimately amorous scenes. Classical themes, mythological subjects, gallantry, decorative allegories, and romantic pastoral scenes (beautifully dressed women in swings in the garden). Chinese and Japanese motifs. Sinuous curves and vegetal designs.",
        geographic_focus: "Hôtel de Soubise, Paris. Paris, France. Austria. Venice, Murano, Italy. Würzburg Residence, Bavaria, Germany.",
        interesting_facts: "The name Rococo was a variation of Rocaille, originally a method of decorating Renaissance grottoes and fountains using pebbles, rocks, seashells and cement.",
        prominant_formats: "Portrait paintings. Interior building decoration and ornamentation. Illusionistic ceiling and wall paintings. Allegories, tapestries, carpets, theatre decoration. Ceramic, porcelain figurines.",
        new_or_dominant_materials: "Decorative items. Molded, painted or white stucco, wood carving with use of different colored woods (usually oak, beech or walnut). Lacquered wood in the Japanese style. Ornaments of gilded gold and bronze. Furniture, Marble tops of commodes or tables. Silverware. Venetian glassware (Murano glass) and multicolour chandeliers, mirrors with extremely ornate frames. Small-scale ceramics and porcelain sculptures and figurines.",
        relevant_images: "null",
        thumbnail: require('../assets/mvmt_images/rococo.jpg'),
    },
